en.purpose: To provide an example of a simple laboratory panel/battery report typical of haematology and clinical chemistry reports using the LOINC terminology.

at0000.1.description: *The findings and interpretation of a pathology laboratory test performed on patient-related specimens.(en)
at0000.1.comment: *This archetype may be used to record a single valued test, but will often be specialised or templated to represent multiple value or 'panel' tests. This archetype also acts as the parent for specialisations appropriate for more specific laboratory tests, e.g. microbiology, histopathology.(en)

at0005.1.description: *Identification of the pathology test performed, sometimes including specimen type and patient state.(en)
at0005.1.comment: *A test result may be for a single analyte, or a group of items, including panel tests. Coding with a terminology, potientially a pre-coordinated term including specimen type, is preferred, where possible. May be coded with LOINC or Snomed-CT. Examples include "Glucose", "Urea and Electrolytes", "Swab",  “Cortisol (am)” or "Liver Biopsy".(en)

at0073.1.description: *The status of the laboratory test result as a whole.(en)

at0075.1.description: *The date and/or time that the entire result was issued for the recorded ‘Test Report Status’.(en)

at0077.1.description: *The diagnostic service that performs the examination.(en)
at0077.1.comment:
*For example, biochemistry, haematology. This helps clinicians filter for broad categories of results accoridng to local laboratory arrangements. Coding with a terminology is desirable, where possible.
(en)

at0100.1.description: *Description of clinical information available at the time of interpretation of results, which may include a link to the original clinical information provided in the test request.(en)
at0100.1.comment: *In HL7 fhir this information is held within the linked requestDetail.clinical Notes.(en)

at0098.1.description: *Single word, phrase or brief description representing the narrative in the 'Conclusion'.(en)
at0098.1.comment: *Coding with a terminology is preferred, where possible.(en)

at0101.1.description: *Additional narrative about the test not captured in other fields.(en)

at0010.1.description: *Rich text or other multimedia  representation of the entire result as issued by the diagnostic service.(en)
at0010.1.comment: *Multiple formats are allowed but they must be semantically equivalent.(en)

at0113.1.description: *Aspects of the condition or cicumstances of the patient that may alter interpretation of the laboratory test.(en)

at0068.1.description: *The local identifier given to the laboratory test result  by the Laboratory Information System.(en)

at0106.1.description: *Identification of the original laboratory test requested, where the test requested differs from the test actually performed.(en)

at0062.1.description: *The local ID assigned to the test order by the order requester.(en)
at0062.1.comment: *Equivalent to the HL7 Placer Order Identifier.(en)

at0063.1.description: *The local ID assigned to the test order by the order filler, usually by the Laboratory Information System (LIS).(en)
at0063.1.comment: *Assigning an identifier to a request by the Laboratory lnformation System (LIS) enables tracking progress of the request and enables linking results to requests. It also provides a reference to assist with enquiries and it is usually equivalent to the HL7 Filler Order Identifier.(en)

at0111.1.description: *True if a point of care device supplies the test result rather than a formal laboratory service.(en)

at0029.1.description: *The type of specimen to be collected e.g venous blood, prostatic biopsy.(en)

at0015.1.description: *The date and time that collection has been ordered to take place or has taken place.(en)

at0008.1.description: *Any conditions to be met before the sample should be taken.(en)
at0008.1.comment:
* e.g. fasting, 'full bladder', 'sterile field' or any special instructions on the handling or immediate processing of the sample e.g. centrifuge on receipt. 

Can also be used to document any known deviations from collection or handling instructions e.g patient was not fasted.(en)

at0007.1.description: *The method of collection to be used eg Venepuncture, biopsy, resection.(en)

at0079.1.description: *Additional detailed description of method of sample collection.(en)

at0005.1.description: *Any risk or biohazard associated with  collecting or handling the specimen.(en)

at0067.1.description:
*Identification of the setting at which the specimen was collected 
from a subject of care. The specimen is often collected by a 
healthcare provider, but may be collected directly by the patient or carer at home.(en)
at0067.1.comment:
*This specifies the specimen collection location within the healthcare
environment. It enables the laboratory to ask questions about the
collection of the specimen, if required. The specimen collection
setting may provide additional information relevant to the analysis 
of the result.(en)

at0070.1.description: *Identifier of the person or agency responsible for collecting the specimen.(en)

at0080.1.description: *The total number of containers holding this specimen.(en)
